   Two-decade tug-of-war over Latin Mass 









       April 2005 
       Pope Benedict XVI is elected 








       July 2007 
       Benedict removes restrictions on celebrating old Latin Mass, reviving a rite all but swept away by 1960s Vatican II meetings that modernized the church










       March 2013 
       Pope Francis is elected









       July 2021 
       Francis reverses Benedict's reform and reimposes restrictions on celebrating old Latin Mass, saying bishops had complained the 2007 reform had become a source of division 





       December 2021 
       Francis doubles down and forbids the celebration of some sacraments according to the ancient rite 





       February 2023 
       Francis imposes further limitations, decreeing that the Holy See must sign off on bishops’ decisions to designate additional parish churches for the Latin Mass or to let newly ordained priests celebrate it 








       May 2025         
       Pope Leo XIV is elected 





       July 2025 
       Leaked Vatican documents undermine Francis’ justification for restrictions, suggesting that most bishops had expressed general satisfaction with the old Latin Mass 





       September 2025 
       In his first interview, Leo says some people have used the liturgy as a political tool but expresses an openness to talk with proponents of the old Latin Mass 




       October 2025 
       Cardinal Raymond Burke, who criticized Francis’ crackdown, celebrates the old Latin Mass in St. Peter’s Basilica 





